    <name>
      <text>7.2.5 (Linear programming 2)</text>
    </name>
    <questiontext format="moodle_auto_format">
      <text><![CDATA[<p>Find the maximum and minimum values of the equation \(z = {@opt@}\) subject to the following constraints 
\[ 
\begin{align*} 
&amp; {@c1@}
\\ 
&amp;{@c2@}
\\ 
&amp; {@c3@}
\end{align*}
\]
</p>
<p>maximum = [[input:ans1]] [[validation:ans1]][[feedback:prt1]]</p>
<p>minimum = [[input:ans2]] [[validation:ans2]][[feedback:prt2]]</p>]]></text>
    </questiontext>
    <generalfeedback format="moodle_auto_format">
      <text><![CDATA[<p> We need to find the corner points of the feasibility region so we could plot the lines 
\[
\begin{align*} 
&amp; {@eqn1@}
\\ 
&amp;{@eqn2@}
\\ 
&amp;{@eqn3@}
\end{align*}
\] 
on the same graph and then read off the coordinates of the corner points, or we could solve each pair of equations simultaneously.</p>

<p>In this case we can see that the coordinates of the corner points are 
\[
({@aa1@},{@aa2@}), \qquad ({@bb1@},{@bb2@}) \qquad \mbox{and} \qquad ({@cc1@},{@cc2@}).
\]
So to find the maximum and minimum with respect to the constraints above, we insert these coordinates into the optimisation equation. This gives us:
\[
\begin{align*}
&({@aa1@},{@aa2@}): z ={@aa@}
\\
&({@bb1@},{@bb2@}): z = {@bb@}
\\
&({@cc1@},{@cc2@}): z = {@cc@}
\end{align*}
\]
Hence the maximum is {@ta1@} and the minimum is {@ta2@}</p>]]></text>
    </generalfeedback>
